"Cubasch U., Kadow C.","Global climate change and aspects of regional climate change in the Berlin-Brandenburg region",2011,"Erde","142","1-2",,"3","20",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-84855790196&partnerID=40&md5=a68cfc3413613262ba127febef90d7e8","Institute of Meteorology, Freie Universität Berlin, Carl-Heinrich-Becker-Weg 6-10, 12165 Berlin, Germany; Helmholtz Centre Potsdam, GFZ German Research Centre for Geosciences, Section 1.3, Earth System Modelling, 14473 Potsdam, Germany","Cubasch, U., Institute of Meteorology, Freie Universität Berlin, Carl-Heinrich-Becker-Weg 6-10, 12165 Berlin, Germany; Kadow, C., Helmholtz Centre Potsdam, GFZ German Research Centre for Geosciences, Section 1.3, Earth System Modelling, 14473 Potsdam, Germany","Climate change in the Berlin-Brandenburg region is compared with globally observed climate change. A temperature record extending over than 300 years and a precipitation record for more than 100 years indicate that climate change can be seen in the climate record of Berlin-Brandenburg as well, where the temperature has risen significantly, at a rate of 0.104°C per decade during the last 100 years. The total number of frost days per year has decreased by almost 17 during the last century; the number of summer days per year has increased significantly by about 12 during the same time. Annual mean precipitation has hardly changed (by less than 0.2 %) during the last century. In summer, rainfall has decreased by about 4 %, and in winter it has increased by 3 %. Precipitation change is not significant at the 95 % confidence level. Model projections indicate that warming will continue which means that Berlin-Brandenburg will experience a temperature rise of about 3-3.5°C by the end of this century for the IPCC scenario A1B. For the same scenario the precipitation will increase by 10-20 % in winter and decrease by 10-30 % in summer. The seasonal precipitation changes compensate each other, resulting in an almost unchanged annual mean.",,"annual variation; climate change; frost; historical record; Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change; precipitation (climatology); proxy climate record; temperature profile; Berlin; Brandenburg [Germany]; Germany",,,,,,"Beck, C., Jacobeit, J., Philipp, A., Variability of North-Atlantic-European circulation patterns since 1780 and corresponding variations in central european climate (2001) Detecting and Modelling Regional Climate Change and Associated Impacts, pp. 321-331. , Brunei, M. and D. Lopez (eds.),Berlin et al; Behre, O., (1908) Das Klima Von Berlin, , Berlin; Bernhardt, K.-H., Mäder, C., Statistische auswertung von berichten über bemerkenswerte witterungsereignisse seit dem jahre 1000 (1987) Zeitschrift für Meteorologie, 37 (2), pp. 120-130; Bogumil, G., (1978) Ergebnisse des Berliner Klimamessnetzes, , Beilage zur Berliner Wetterkarte, Institut für Meteorologie, Freie Universität Berlin, published annually; Brand, K.A., (1757) Wettertagebücher 1757 bis 1794, , Offenbach; Cubasch, U., Kadow, C., Die berliner temperaturreihe (2010) Acta Historica Astronomiae, 41, pp. 112-132; Cubasch, U., Kadow, C., Temperaturaufzeichnungen in Berlin für die letzten 310 Jahre (2011) Globaler Wandel und Regionale Entwicklung: Anpassungsstrategien in der Region Berlin-Brandenburg, pp. 30-36. , Hiittl, R.F., R. Emmermann, S. Germer, M. Naumann und O. Bens (Hrsg.), Heidelberg; Temperaturverhältnisse (Tabellen) (1971) Abhandlungen des Meteorologischen Dienstes der DDR, 103. , Das Klima von Berlin, 2; Gerstengarbe, F.-W., Badeck, F., Hattermann, F., Krysanova, V., Lahmer, W., Lasch, P., Stock, M., Werner, P.C., Studie zur klimatischen entwicklung im land brandenburg bis 2055 und deren auswirkungen auf den wasserhaushalt, die forst- und landwirtschaft sowie die ableitung erster perspektiven (2003) PIK Report, 83. , Potsdam; Givati, A., Rosenfeld, D., Quantifying precipitation suppression due to air pollution (2004) Journal of Applied Meteorology, 43 (7), pp. 